<p>Do I need a "*.example.com" SSL certificate to do this? I only have a "www.example.com" certificate.</p>  <p>Tried the below with no luck: </p>  <p>1) <a href="http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/rewrite/remapping.html#canonicalhost" rel="nofollow">http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/rewrite/remapping.html#canonicalhost</a></p>  <p>2) <a href="http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/rewrite/avoid.html" rel="nofollow">http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/rewrite/avoid.html</a></p>  <p>3) <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/5151112/how-to-redirect-https-example-com-to-https-www-example-com">How to Redirect https://example.com/ to https://www.example.com/</a></p>  <p>Original before changes:</p>  <pre><code>&lt;VirtualHost *:80&gt;       ServerName www.example.com     Redirect / https://www.example.com/ &lt;/VirtualHost &gt;     &lt;VirtualHost *:443&gt;         DocumentRoot /var/www/html     ServerName www.example.com     SSLEngine on     SSLCertificateFile www_example_com.crt     SSLCertificateKeyFile www_example_com.key     SSLCertificateChainFile File.crt      Options +FollowSymLinks     RewriteEngine On     RewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} !-d     RewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} !-f      RewriteRule ^([^\.]+)$ $1.php [NC]     RewriteRule ^/m/([0-9]+)\.php/?$ /msg.php?t=$1 [NC] &lt;/VirtualHost&gt; </code></pre>